-- Japan, India, China, Indonesia, Thailand: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview
-- Andrea Wong
-- 2010-09-20T23:08:21Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-20/japan-india-china-indonesia-thailand-asia-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 The Cabinet Office will release at 2 p.m. in Tokyo its
final report on Japan’s coincident and leading indices for July.  
 The Ministry of Finance will announce at 10:30 a.m. in
Tokyo the amount of two-year Japanese government bonds it plans
to sell on Sept. 28.  
 The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 1.07 percent on Sept. 17, according to Japan Bond
Trading Co., the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 Japan’s financial markets were closed for a public holiday
yesterday.  
 The yen traded at 87.73 per dollar at 8:04 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 India: The government plans to raise as much as 30 billion
rupees ($657 million) by selling three-month and one-year
treasury bills tomorrow. It will offer 20 billion rupees of 91-
day securities and 10 billion rupees of 364-day notes, according
to the central bank.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due in May 2020 was
7.971 percent. The rupee was at 45.63.  
 Thailand: The government will sell a combined 89 billion
baht ($2.9 billion) of 28-, 91- and 182-day bills as well as 3-
year bonds.  
 The yield on the 3.625 percent note maturing May 2015 was
2.75 percent. The baht was at 30.76.  
 Indonesia: Indonesia plans to sell a total of 3 trillion
rupiah ($334 million) of bonds and bills in an auction today,
the Finance Ministry’s debt management office said on Sept. 16.
It will sell 1-year treasury notes and 5-year and 15-year bonds.  
 The yield on the 11 percent bond due in November 2020 was
7.865 percent, according to the Inter Dealer Market Association.
The rupiah was at 8,978 per dollar.  
 China: The People’s Bank of China will sell 19 billion
yuan ($2.83 billion) of one-year bills, 14 billion yuan of 3-
month bills, and 5 billion yuan of three-year bills tomorrow,
the central bank said in a statement on its website today.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due June 2015 was 2.646
percent. The yuan was at 6.7143.  
 To contact the reporter on this story:
 Andrea Wong  in Hong Kong at 
 awong268@bloomberg.net   
          
          


  
     
       
     
           
                           
                 
                 
                                       
                                   
               
                        
           
                          Sept. 20 (Bloomberg) -- Todd Martin, equity strategist at Societe Generale, talks about his investment strategy for Asian stocks.
     Asian stocks fell, led by raw-material producers, after an unexpected drop in U.S. consumer confidence. Martin also discusses U.S., Chinese and Indian economies. He talks with Rishaad Salamat on Bloomberg Television's "On the Move Asia." (Source: Bloomberg)  
                           

     
